message.content: A 'Calidris bairdii' is a small shorebird species that typically measures around 18 cm in length. It has a plump, round shape with a short neck and small head. Its feathers are mottled light and dark brown with a white belly. The beak is straight and fairly long, measuring around 2.5 cm in length. Overall, the 'Calidris bairdii' has a slightly chunky appearance. It is commonly found on the arctic tundra during breeding season, and migrates to the coasts of South America during the non-breeding season. Its unique visual characteristics make it stand out among other shorebirds.
